record_data.record_title: RAVENSWOOD BAY TUNNEL BORING MACHINE REMOVAL PROJECT
record_data.record_plain_text:
Agreement Between the City and County of San Francisco and Pacific Gas and Electric Company for the Ravenswood Bay Tunnel Boring Machine Interconnection Facilities Removal Project 1. Purpose City and County of San Francisco (“CCSF”) has requested that Pacific Gas and Electric Company (“PG&E”) remove certain facilities serving CCSF’s Ravenswood Bore Bay Tunnel Project (“Project”) that PG&E installed for CCSF pursuant to a Transmission Facilities Agreement (“TFA”) executed on November 6, 2009 and filed with the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (“FERC”) on November 9, 2009, under PG&E Rate Schedule FERC No. 243. This Removal Agreement (“Agreement”), inclusive of Exhibits A and B, is entered into as an amendment to the TFA and incorporates all of the provisions contained in Exhibit B to the TFA. 2. Background Pursuant to the TFA, PG&E installed a 115 kV temporary service to CCSF’s Project. CCSF’s Project is now complete and, pursuant to Section 8 of the TFA, CCSF has requested that PG&E remove its service facilities. 3. Work Requested The work requested by CCSF will involve transmission Tower #0/4, on the Ravenswood – Ames #1 115 kV line, which is about 3,000-foot south of Ravenswood Substation, as well as system protection reconfiguration at Ravenswood Substation and Ames Substation. The attached Exhibit A shows the transmission lines involved and the work locations. The following work is necessary to remove PG&E’s equipment at the locations described above and to restore PG&E’s system protection to its original configuration: × Remove the 100-foot, 115 kV tap line to the CCSF substation. × Remove PG&E’s high-side metering and any PG&E-owned equipment from the CCSF substation. × Reconfigure the line current differential protection scheme for the Ravenswood – Ames #1 115 kV line. This requires converting the existing 3-terminal configuration to a 2-teminal configuration for both relays and protection communications. × Reconfigure the fiber-optic cable used for the current differential protection scheme at the Ravenswood – Ames #1 115 kV line, and convert from 3-terminal to 2-terminal protection communications. 4. Project Payment Schedule CCSF’s payment for removal of the facilities will be in phases as shown in Exhibit B. On or about March 6, 2015, PG&E will issue an invoice to CCSF in the amount of $250,000 for the Phase I payment. PG&E will issue a second invoice at a later date for the Phase 2 payment. While the Phase 2 payment is currently estimated at $250,000 that estimate may be updated as a result of the engineering work performed under Phase 1. Collectively the payments for Phases 1 and 2 are CCSF’s “Advance Payment.” Within 30 days of CCSF’s receipt of a PG&E invoice (for both Phase 1 and Phase 2), CCSF shall pay PG&E the full amount of the invoice. PG&E will begin work immediately upon receipt of the Phase 1 payment. 5. Financial Accounting Upon Work Completion Within 120 business days after PG&E determines that the work described in Section 3 is complete, PG&E will determine its actual costs, which will include the salvage value of any of the removed equipment (“Actual Cost”). If the Actual Cost is less than CCSF’s Advance Payment, then PG&E shall refund the difference to CCSF within 120 business days after the completion of the work. If the Actual Cost exceeds the Advance Payment, PG&E shall issue an invoice to CCSF for the difference within 120 business days after the completion of the work. If PG&E issues an invoice to CCSF under this Agreement, CCSF must pay in full within 30 days of receipt of the invoice. An invoice shall be deemed received on the third business day after the postmarked date unless a copy of the invoice is sent electronically, in which case it shall be deemed received on the same day. If CCSF disputes all or any portion of the invoice submitted by PG&E, CCSF must first pay the invoice in full and then endeavor to resolve any billing dispute pursuant to Section 9.29 of the CCSF IA. 6. Parties’ Addresses CCSF’s address for any invoices or notices required under this Agreement is: Pamela HusingManager, Wholesale and Retail ServicesPower EnterpriseSan Francisco Public Utilities Commission525 Golden Gate Avenue, 7th floorSan Francisco, CA 94102Email: phusing@sfwater.orgTel: (415) 554-2469 PG&E’s address for any invoices or notices required under this Agreement is: Yilma HailemichaelManager, Electric Transmission Contract ManagementMail Code B13LPacific Gas and Electric CompanyP.O. Box 770000San Francisco, CA 94177-0001Email: vxh4@pge.com CCSF should send payments to the following address: PG&E CFM / PPC DEPARTMENT P.O. BOX 997340 SACRAMENTO, CA 95899-7340 Please include the following tracking numbers on the any checks associated with this Agreement: PM Order # 31133675 7. Access CCSF hereby grants to PG&E the right of ingress and egress from CCSF’s premises at all reasonable hours for any purpose reasonably connected with the work described in Section 3. Notwithstanding the foregoing, PG&E will make sure that its work does not interfere with CCSF’s use of the premises. Whenever part or all of the requested work is to be performed upon property other than that of CCSF, CCSF shall first procure from such owners all necessary rights-of-way or permits in a form satisfactory to PG&E and without cost to PG&E. 8. Force Majeure PG&E shall not be responsible for any delay in completion of the removal of the facilities resulting from shortage of labor or materials, strike, labor disturbance, war, riot, weather conditions, governmental rule, regulation or order, including orders or judgments of any court or regulatory agency, delay in obtaining necessary rights of way and easements, acts of God, delays resulting from PG&E’s responsibility to coordinate certain electric interconnections with the California Independent System Operator Corporation or any other cause or condition beyond the control of PG&E, nor shall PG&E be liable for incidental, indirect, special, punitive, or consequential damages for any such delay. PG&E shall have the right, if for one of the above reasons it is unable to obtain materials or labor for all of its construction and removal requirements, to allocate materials and labor to construction and removal projects which it deems, in its sole discretion, most important to serve the needs of its customers, and any delay in removal hereunder resulting from such allocation shall be deemed to be a cause beyond PG&E’s control. In the event that PG&E is prevented from completing the removal of the facilities for reasons beyond its control after twelve months following the date of this Agreement, PG&E shall have the right to supersede this Agreement, upon at least 30 days’ written notice to CCSF, and adjust any amounts paid or required to be paid by CCSF based on that portion of the facilities then removed, if any, utilizing the estimated costs developed by PG&E for this Agreement. 9. Effective Date Subject to CCSF’s reservation of rights as set forth below, this Agreement shall become effective on the later of: (1) March 6, 2015 or (2) on the date FERC permits this Agreement to become effective without any changes that either party in its sole judgment deems material. Except as provided for herein, this Agreement shall remain in force until the facilities are removed, the final accounting and final true-up payment associated with this removal has been paid. 10. Jurisdiction This Agreement shall be subject to all of PG&E’s tariffs, as applicable under federal law, on file with and authorized by FERC, and shall at all times be subject to such changes or modifications as FERC may direct from time to time in the exercise of its jurisdiction. Nothing contained herein shall be construed as affecting in any way the right of PG&E to unilaterally make application to FERC for a change in rates under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act (“FPA”) and pursuant to FERC’s Rules and Regulations promulgated thereunder; CCSF shall have the right to protest and object to such proposed change in rates and otherwise to exercise any and all rights it may have with respect thereto, including its rights under Section 206 of the FPA. The term “rates” as used herein shall mean all rates, charges, terms and conditions contained in this Agreement. A change in rates may include, but is not limited to, changes in rates and charges and also may include changes in the underlying methodology by which such rates and charges are developed. 11. Disputes Any dispute arising from this Agreement shall be resolved in accordance with dispute resolution procedures contained in Section 9.29 of Exhibit B of the TFA. 12. Execution IN WITNESS WHEREOF, the Parties have caused this Agreement to be executed by authorized representatives this day of March, 2015, and it will be effective as set forth above.

record_data.record_plain_text: Provisions Sourced from the 2007 Interconnection Agreement 1. Definitions 1.39. Good Utility Practice - Practices, standards, methods and procedures that are commonly used to plan for and operate, an electric utility’s system safely, reliably, and economically with due regard for effects on other interconnected utilities, applicable laws, governmental rules, regulations and orders, conservation of natural resources and protection of the environment. Such practices, standards, methods and procedures shall be within the scope of those engaged in or approved by and commonly used by utilities that: (I) are located in the State of California, and (ii) operate a Control Area recognized by the Western Electricity Coordinating Council. 3. Transmission and Distribution 3.3 Transmission and Distribution Facilities 3.3.2. Special Facilities - If, in order to satisfy a request for service by City pursuant to the TFA, PG&E is required to (a) install transmission or distribution facilities which are in addition to or in substitution for the standard facilities which PG&E normally provides for transmission or distribution service or (b) allocate facilities for the sole use of City which would not normally be allocated for the sole use of City, City shall pay the costs of those facilities, including such continuing ownership costs as may be applicable, as set forth in PG&E’s then current Electric Rule No.2 or successor on file with the California Public Utilities Commission (“CPUC”). 3.3.3. Additional Facilities and Additional City Load - If it is necessary for PG&E to extend, reinforce, or change in any way its standard transmission, distribution or service facilities or to perform any other line extension or reinforcement work to furnish firm transmission service or firm distribution Service to any City load, City and PG&E will pay the additional cost of such extensions or reinforcements as set forth in PG&E’s then current Electric Rule Nos. 15, 15.2 and 16 or successor(s) on file with the CPUC; provided, that if any new or additional facilities are needed to provide firm transmission service or firm distribution service to any single new or additional City load with a demand of 500 kW or more, City shall pay the costs as determined in accordance with the standard service facilities provisions of PG&E’s large commercial and industrial retail rate schedule, Schedule E-20, or its successor on file with the CPUC. 8. Accounting, Metering, Billing and Payment 8.3. Billing and Payment 8.3.3. Any amount due under this TFA that is not paid on time i shall accrue interest from the date payment is due until the date payment is received. The interest rate applicable to any payment or refund due during a given Billing Period shall be the rate for refunds calculated pursuant to 18 C.F.R. Section 35.1 9a of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (“FERC”) Regulations, as that section may be amended or superseded from time to time. The monthly interest rate shall be prorated by days from the date payment is due until the date payment is received. Interest shall be added to the principal due under the bills; provided, that nothing in this Section 8.3.3 shall be construed to compel either Party to violate any applicable usury laws. 9. General Provisions 9.2. Advancing Costs 9.2.5. PG&E shall provide City a final accounting of the cost of constructing or reinforcing facilities within a reasonable time after the completion of such work. City shall make an additional payment to PG&E, or PG&E shall make a refund to City, as appropriate, in order to adjust for any difference between the estimated and actual costs of such construction or reinforcements. All adjustments shall include an interest component, calculated in accordance with Section 8.3.3, from either (a) the due dates of the estimated billings being adjusted, in the case of an additional payment, or (b) the dates payments were received by PG&E, in the case of a refund, to the dates the refunds or additional payments are paid. City shall have audit rights as provided in Section 9.5. 9.2.6. If City advances PG&E funds to construct or reinforce PG&E’s transmission facilities to meet City’s transmission requirements, PG&E may use, for its own purposes or to provide transmission service to third parties, any transmission capacity made available by such construction or reinforcement beyond that required to serve City under this TFA. If PG&E uses such transmission capacity for itself or to serve third parties, PG&E will compensate City for such use in a manner to be agreed upon and as described in the TFA. 9.5 Audit Rights City or its agents shall have the right to audit PG&E’s supporting documents upon which PG&E bases its bills and costs to City for a period up to two (2) years after the later of receipt of the final accounting or receipt of the final bill for such costs. 9.17. Liability 9.17.1. Rights of Third Parties - Nothing in this Agreement shall be construed to create any duty to, any standard of care with reference to, or any liability or obligation, contractual or otherwise, to any Third Party. 9.17.2. Between Parties 9.17.2.1. Except for its willful misconduct or with respect to nonpayment of money due, neither Party, nor its directors or members of its governing board, officers, employees or agents shall be liable to the other Party for any loss, damage, claim, cost, charge or expense arising from performance or nonperformance under this TFA. 9.17.2.2. Each Party shall be responsible for protecting its facilities from possible damage by reason of electrical disturbances or faults caused by the operation, faulty operation, or nonoperation of the other Party’s facilities, and such other Party shall not be liable for any such damages so caused. 9.17.3. For Interruptions - PG&E shall not be liable to City, and City hereby releases PG&E and its directors, officers, employees and agents from any claim, demand, liability, loss or damage, whether direct, indirect or consequential, incurred by City, which results from the interruption or curtailment of electric service made available by PG&E under this TFA. 9.29. Settlement of Disputes and Arbitration 9.29.1. Good Faith Efforts by the Parties and Informal Dispute Resolution Procedures - In the normal course of business, the Parties shall attempt in good faith and using best efforts to resolve any dispute arising out of or relating to this TFA through the informal dispute resolution procedures specified herein. If the Parties are unable to resolve a dispute, the informal dispute resolution provisions of this Section 9.29.1 shall apply. Informal dispute resolution procedures shall include discussion and negotiation between managers who have authority to settle the dispute and who are at a higher level of management than the persons with direct responsibility for administration and management of the TFA. To clarify the nature and scope of the dispute before involving higher level management, the Party raising a dispute shall provide to the other Party a written description of all issues regarding the dispute, the approximate amount of money or other burden involved and the Party’s proposed resolution of the dispute. The receiving Party shall provide in response a written explanation of its position and proposed resolution within fifteen (15) days. Within ten (10) days after the receiving Party provides its response, managers of the Parties shall meet to try to resolve the dispute. The Parties may agree to additional meetings after this initial meeting, or either Party may initiate the formal dispute resolution procedures in Section 9.29.2. 9.29.2. Initiation of Formal Dispute and Negotiation Between Executives - If the Parties are unable to resolve the dispute through the informal dispute resolution procedures in Section 9.29.1, either Party may initiate a formal dispute by submitting written notice to the other Party stating: (1) the nature of the dispute, a statement of the Party’s position and a summary of the arguments supporting its position, and (2) the name and title of the executive who will be the designated representative of that Party and any other person(s) who will accompany the executive. Within twenty-one (21) days of receipt of the formal notice, the receiving Party shall respond with: (1) a statement of that Party’s position and a summary of arguments supporting that position, and (2) the name and title of the executive who will be the designated representative of that Party and any other person(s) who will accompany the executive. For PG&E, the designated executive shall be at least at the level of a Vice President; for City, the designated executive shall be at least at the level of the Assistant General Manager. Within forty (40) days after delivery of the formal notice, the designated representatives of both Parties shall meet at a mutually acceptable time and place and thereafter as often as they deem reasonably necessary to attempt to resolve the dispute. All reasonable requests for information made by one Party to the other will be honored. 9.29.3. Mediation - If the executives for both Parties are unable to resolve the dispute within sixty (60) days of the initiating Party’s formal notice of dispute or the Parties fail to meet within forty (40) days after delivery of the formal notice of dispute, either Party may submit the dispute to non-binding mediation by providing written notice to the other Party. The Parties agree to meet and confer and select a mediator within thirty (30) days of the written notice of submission to mediation. The mediator and the designated representative of each Party with authority to settle the dispute shall meet within twenty-one (21) days after appointment of the mediator. The Parties shall attempt in good faith to resolve their dispute in accordance with the procedures and timetable established by the mediator. If either Party concludes that the mediation efforts have reached an impasse, it may provide a written declaration so stating to the other Party. Such written declaration of impasse shall set forth the date forty-five (45) days hence by which arbitration must be commenced to avoid waiver of claims. For matters not excepted pursuant to Section 9.29.6 from the scope of these dispute resolution procedures or from the provisions related to binding arbitration, if neither Party commences arbitration under Section 9.29.4 within forty-five (45) days after the delivery of a written declaration that mediation efforts have reached an impasse, both Parties shall be deemed to have waived all present claims with respect to such dispute. 9.29.4. Binding Arbitration - After a written declaration of impasse in mediation is provided pursuant to Section 9.29.3, either Party may commence binding arbitration by serving a written demand for arbitration upon the other Party. The written demand for arbitration shall set forth in reasonable detail the nature of the dispute, the claims for which arbitration is demanded, the Party’s position, the grounds supporting its position and the remedy being sought by the arbitration. Within twenty-one (21) days of the receipt of the written demand for arbitration, the other Party shall serve a written response upon the initiating Party stating its understanding of the issues in dispute, its position, the grounds supporting its position and its proposed remedy. Within forty-five (45) days after delivery of the initiating Party’s written demand for arbitration, the Parties shall agree on a single arbitrator who must be knowledgeable about electricity markets in California or other wholesale electricity markets. If the Parties cannot agree on an arbitrator within forty-five (45) days after delivery of the initiating Party’s written demand for arbitration, the Parties will request the American Arbitration Association (“AAA”) to provide the names of three qualified arbitrators, and the arbitrator will be selected from among those three arbitrators. Each Party shall within ten (10) days from receipt of the names from AAA strike one of the three names from the list provided by AAA. The remaining arbitrator shall be the person who hears the arbitration. All arbitrators whose names are provided by AAA must be knowledgeable about electricity markets in California or other wholesale electricity markets and experts in the subject matter of the dispute and shall have no official, financial, or personal conflict of interest with respect to the Parties or the issues involved in the dispute, unless such interest is fully disclosed in writing to both Parties and both Parties waive in writing any objection to the interest. Within five (5) days after selection, the Parties shall submit to the arbitrator the written notice and submittal statements prepared pursuant to this Section 9.29.4. Within ten (10) days after selection of the arbitrator, the Parties shall meet with the arbitrator to establish the arbitration schedule, including deadlines for discovery, the hearing date(s), the post hearing briefing schedule and the time for the arbitrator to issue a decision. Subject to the Parties’ overriding objective that fairness and due process be achieved, the schedule shall seek to result in a decision by the arbitrator being issued within six (6) months of the Parties’ initial meeting with the arbitrator. Except as otherwise provided in this Section 9.29.4, the arbitration shall be governed by the Commercial Arbitration Rules of the AAA, as they may be in effect as of the date of the demand for arbitration. The nature and extent of permissible discovery shall be determined by the arbitrator, taking into account: (a) the complexity of the dispute, (b) the extent to which facts are disputed, and (c) the amount of money in controversy. The decision of the arbitrator shall be in writing and shall include findings with respect to each issue involved in the dispute. The arbitrator shall issue his or her decision within thirty (30) days of receipt of the final written brief or oral argument. The arbitrator shall specify the time within which the Parties shall comply with the decision. The decision of the arbitrator may be enforced by any court or agency having jurisdiction over the Party against whom the decision is rendered. In addition to any legal remedies to enforce the arbitrator’s decision, the failure of either Party to abide by the decision or, if the decision is appealed, the failure to abide by the final appellate decision on the arbitrator’s decision, by immediately taking whatever action is necessary to comply with that decision and completing the compliance within a reasonable time after the decision becomes final shall cause, at the sole discretion of the other Party, to invoke the termination provisions of Section 9.26 of this TFA. The arbitrator shall have no authority, power or jurisdiction to alter, amend, change or modify any provision of this TFA, including this Section 9.29. The decision of the arbitrator shall be final, binding and not appealable, except as provided in California Code of Civil Procedure sections 1286.2 and 1286.6. The Parties shall take whatever action is required to comply with the arbitrator’s decision. All costs of the arbitration shall be paid equally by the Parties. Each Party shall be responsible for its own costs and expenses, including attorneys’ fees. 9.29.5. Confidentiality - All negotiations to resolve disputes pursuant to Sections 9.29.1 through 9.29.3, including through informal and formal dispute resolution procedures and mediation, are confidential and shall be treated as compromise and settlement negotiations for the purposes of California and Federal Rules of Evidence and FERC Rule 602. 9.29.6. Scope of Dispute Resolution Provisions - The dispute resolution provisions in Section 9.29 shall apply to all disputes under this TFA except: (1) the provisions related to binding arbitration, including the requirement to commence arbitration within a specified time period, shall not apply to disputes concerning any rate specified in the TFA over which FERC has jurisdiction; (2) matters as to which either Party is authorized to make a Section 205 or Section 206 filing at FERC pursuant to Section 9.28 of this TFA or (3) disputes about the validity of this TFA. Disputes concerning the excepted matters listed in the preceding sentence shall be adjudicated by FERC or, if FERC declines to accept jurisdiction over the dispute, by the courts. 9.29.7. TFA to Extend Deadlines - All time limits and deadlines established for dispute resolution procedures under Section 9.29 may be extended by written agreement of the Parties. Time periods expressed in days in the dispute resolution procedures refer to calendar days, not business days. 9.33. City Standard Contract Requirements This Section 9.33 is included to comply with certain City ordinances requiring the inclusion of certain terms and conditions in contracts with the City. To the extent this Section 9.33 would conflict with the Federal Power Act, or rules, regulations, or orders issued under that act, or would interfere with FERC jurisdiction, each Party shall be relieved of any obligation or denied any right to the extent necessary to avoid the conflict or interference. “ Subcontractor” as used in this Section 9.33 means a third party with whom PG&E enters into a contract to perform an obligation under this TFA, but subcontractor, whether or not capitalized, shall not include attorneys or law firms retained by PG&E in connection with advice or disputes arising under or related to this TFA. 9.33.1. Certification of Funds: Budget and Fiscal Provisions; Termination in the Event of Non-Appropriation This TFA is subject to the budget and fiscal provisions of the City’s Charter. Charges will accrue only after prior written authorization certified by the Controller, and the amount of City’s obligation hereunder shall not at any time exceed the amount certified for the purpose and period stated in such advance authorization. This TFA will terminate without penalty, liability or expense of any kind to the City at the end of any fiscal year if funds are not appropriated for the next succeeding fiscal year. If funds are appropriated for a portion of the fiscal year, this TFA will terminate, without penalty, liability or expense of any kind at the end of the term for which funds are appropriated. City has no obligation to make appropriations for this TFA in lieu of appropriations for new or other agreements. City budget decisions are subject to the discretion of the Mayor and the Board of Supervisors. Contractor’s assumption of risk of possible non-appropriation is part of the consideration for this TFA. THIS SECTION CONTROLS AGAINST ANY AND ALL OTHER PROVISIONS OF THIS TFA. 9.33.2. Nondiscriminatory Employment and Business Opportunities Practices 9.33.2.1. Non Discrimination In the performance of this TFA, PG&E agrees not to discriminate on the basis of the fact or perception of a person’s race, color, creed, religion, national origin, ancestry, age, sex, height, weight, sexual orientation, gender identity, domestic partner status, marital status, disability or Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome or HIV status (AIDSIHIV status) against any employee of, any City employee working with, or applicant for employment with, PG&E in any of PG&E’s operations within the United States, or against any person seeking accommodations, advantages, facilities, privileges, services, or membership in all business, social, or other establishments or organizations operated by PG&E. 9.33.2.2. Subcontracts PG&E shall incorporate by reference in all subcontracts the provisions of § 12B.2(a), 12B.2(c)-(k), and 1 2C.3 of the San Francisco Administrative Code (copies of which are available from the City) and shall require all subcontractors to comply with such provisions. PG&E’s failure to comply with the obligations in this Section 9.33.2 shall constitute a material breach of this TFA. 9.33.2.3. Non-Discrimination of Benefits PG&E does not as of the date of this TFA and will not during the term of this TFA, in any of its operations in San Francisco, or where any part of this TFA is being performed for the City elsewhere in the United States, discriminate in the provision of bereavement leave, family medical leave, health benefits, membership or membership discounts, moving expenses, pension or retirement benefits or travel benefits, as well as any benefits other than the benefits specified above, between employees with domestic partners and employees with spouses, and/or between the domestic partners and spouses of such employees, where the domestic partnership has been registered with a governmental entity pursuant to state or local law authorizing registration. 9.33.2.4. Declaration To the extent required by law, PG&E shall execute the “Chapter 1 2B Declaration: Nondiscrimination in Contracts and Benefits” form (form HRC 12B- 101) with supporting documentation. 9.33.3. Conflicts of Interest PG&E acknowledges that it is aware of section 15.103 of City’s Charter (“Conflict of Interest”), Article III, Chapter 2 of City’s Campaign and Governmental Conduct Code (“Conflict of Interest and Other Prohibited Activities”), and section 87100 et seq. and section l090 et seq. of the Government Code of the State of California. 9.33.4. Faith and Fair Dealing with the City Pursuant to section 21.35 of the San Francisco Administrative Code (“Administrative Code”) the covenant of good faith and fair dealing is incorporated into contracts with the City as defined in section 21.02 of the Administrative Code. Contractors and subcontractors shall at all times deal in good faith with the City and shall submit claims, requests for equitable adjustments, requests for change orders, requests for contract modifications or requests of any kind seeking increased compensation on a City contract only upon a good-faith, honest evaluation of the underlying circumstances and a good-faith, honest calculation of the amount sought. PG&E acknowledges that it is aware of section 21.35 of the Administrative Code (“Submitting False Claims”). 9.33.5. Notification of Limitations on Contributions PG&E acknowledges that it is aware of section 1.126 of City’s Campaign and Governmental Conduct Code, which prohibits any person who contracts with the City for the rendition of personal services or for the furnishing of any material, supplies or equipment to the City, from making any campaign contribution to (a) an individual holding a City elective office if the contract must be approved by the individual, a board on which that individual serves, or a board on which an appointee of that individual serves, (b) a candidate for the office held by such individual, or (c) a committee controlled by such individual, at any time from the commencement of negotiations for the contract until the later of either the termination of negotiations for such contract or six months after the date the contract is approved. The foregoing restriction applies only if the contract or a combination or series of contracts approved by the same individual or board in a fiscal year have a total anticipated or actual value of $50,000 (fifty thousand dollars) or more. The prohibition on contributions applies to each prospective party to the contract; each member of Contractor’s board of directors; Contractor’s chairperson, chief executive officer, chief financial officer and chief operating officer; any person with an ownership interest of more than 20 percent in Contractor; any subcontractor listed in the bid or contract; and any committee that is sponsored or controlled by Contractor. Additionally, PG&E acknowledges that it must inform each of the persons described in the preceding sentence of the prohibitions contained in section 1.126. 9.33.6. Prohibition on Political Activity with City Funds In accordance with San Francisco Administrative Code Chapter 12.G, PG&E shall not use City funds received under this TFA to participate in, support, or attempt to influence any political campaign for a candidate or for a ballot measure (collectively, “Political Activity”). The terms and provisions of Chapter 1 2.G are incorporated herein by this reference. In the event PG&E violates the provisions of this section, the City may, in addition to any other rights or remedies available hereunder, (i) terminate this TFA, subject to any necessary regulatory approvals, and (ii) prohibit PG&E from bidding on or receiving any new City contract for a period of two (2) years. The City will not consider PG&E’s use of funds for Political Activity as a violation of this section when PG&E has received revenue or other funds from sources other than the City and such funds are equal to or greater than those funds received under this TFA. When PG&E has received such funds from other sources that are equal to or greater than those funds derived from this TFA, then PG&E will be deemed not to have used any funds appropriated by the City on any Political Activity. 9.33.7. Requiring Minimum Compensation for Covered Employees PG&E agrees to comply fully with and be bound by all of the provisions of the Minimum Compensation Ordinance (“MCO”), as set forth in San Francisco Administrative Code Chapter 12P (Chapter 12P), including the remedies provided, and implementing guidelines and rules. The provisions of Chapter 12P are incorporated herein by reference and made a part of this TFA as though fully set forth. Capitalized term used in this Section 9.33.7 and not defined in this TFA shall have the meanings assigned to such terms in Chapter 1 2P. To the extent consistent with the requirements of the MCO, PG&E agrees to the following: 9.33.7.1. For each hour worked by a Covered Employee during a Pay Period on work funded under the City contract during the term of this TFA, PG&E shall provide to the Covered Employee no less than the Minimum Compensation, which includes a minimum hourly wage and compensated and uncompensated time off consistent with the requirements of the MCO. For the hourly gross compensation portion of the MCO, the PG&E shall pay $9.00 (nine dollars) an hour. 9.33.7.2. PG&E shall not discharge, reduce in compensation, or otherwise discriminate against any employee for complaining to the City with regard to PG&E’s compliance or anticipated compliance with the requirements of the MCO, for opposing any practice proscribed by the MCO, for participating in proceedings related to the MCO, or for seeking to assert or enforce any rights under the MCO by any lawful means. 9.33.7.3. PG&E agrees that any failure to comply with the requirements of the MCO shall constitute a material breach by PG&E of the terms of this TFA. 9.33.7.4. If, within thirty (30) days after receiving written notice of a breach of this TFA for violating the MCO, PG&E fails to cure such breach or, if such breach cannot reasonably be cured within such period of thirty (30) days, PG&E fails to commence efforts to cure within such period, or thereafter fails diligently to pursue such cure to completion, the City, acting through its City Attorney, shall have the right to pursue the following rights or remedies and any rights or remedies available under applicable law: (a) The right to charge PG&E an amount equal to the difference between the Minimum Compensation and any compensation actually provided to a Covered Employee, together with interest on such amount from the date payment was due at the maximum rate then permitted by law; (b) The right to set off all or any portion of the amount described in subsection (d)(1) of this Section 9.33.7 against amounts due to PG&E under this TFA; (c) The right to terminate this TFA in whole or in part, subject to any necessary regulatory approvals; (d) In the event of a breach by PG&E of the covenant referred to in subsection (b) of this Section, the right to seek reinstatement of the employee or to obtain other appropriate equitable relief; and (e) The right to bar PG&E from entering into future contracts with the City for three (3) years. Each of the rights provided in this subsection 9.33.7.4 shall be exercisable individually or in combination with any other rights or remedies available to the City. Any amounts realized by the City pursuant to this subsection (d) shall be paid to the Covered Employee who failed to receive the required Minimum Compensation. 9.33.7.5. PG&E represents and warrants that it is not an entity that was set up, or is being used, for the purpose of evading the intent of the MCO. 9.33.7.6. PG&E shall keep itself informed of the current requirements of the MCO, including increases to the hourly gross compensation due Covered Employees under the MCO, and shall provide prompt written notice to all Covered Employees of any increases in compensation, as well as any written communications received PG&E from the City marked to indicate that they are to be distributed to Covered Employees. 9.33.7.7. PG&E shall provide reports to the City in accordance with any reporting standards promulgated by the City under the MCO, including reports on subcontractors. 9.33.7.8. PG&E shall provide the City with access to pertinent records after receiving a written request from the City to do so and being provided at least five (5) business days to respond. 9.33.7.9. The City may conduct random audits of PG&E. Random audits shall be (a) noticed in advance in writing; (b) limited to ascertaining whether Covered Employees are paid at least the minimum compensation required by the MCO; (c) accomplished through an examination of pertinent records at a mutually agreed upon time and location within ten (10) days of the written notice; and (d) limited to one audit of PG&E every two years for the duration of this TFA. Nothing in this TFA is intended to preclude the City from investigating any report of an alleged violation of the MCO. 9.33.7.10. Any subcontract entered into by PG&E shall require the subcontractor to comply with the requirements of the MCO and shall contain contractual obligations substantially the same as those set forth in this Section 9.33.7. A subcontract means an agreement between PG&E and a third party which requires the third party to perform all or a portion of the services covered by this TFA. PG&E shall ensure that any subcontractors of any tier under this TFA comply with the requirements of the MCO. If any subcontractor under this TFA fails to comply, City may pursue any of the remedies set forth in this Section 9.33.7 against PG&E, provided that City has first provided PG&E with notice and an opportunity to cure the violation. 9.33.7.11. Each Covered Employee is a third-party beneficiary with respect to the requirements of subsections (a) and (b) of this Section 9.33.7, and may pursue the following remedies in the event of a breach by PG&E of subsections (a) and (b), but only after the Covered Employee has provided the notice, participated in the administrative review hearing, and waited the 21-day period required by the MCO. PG&E understands and agrees that if the Covered Employee prevails in such action, the Covered Employee may be awarded: (a) an amount equal to the difference between the Minimum Compensation and any compensation actually provided to the Covered Employee, together with Interest on such amount from the date payment was due at the maximum rate then permitted by law; (b) in the event of a breach by PG&E of subsections (a) or (b), the right to seek reinstatement or to obtain other appropriate equitable relief; and (c) in the event that the Covered Employee is the prevailing party in any legal action or proceeding against PG&E arising from this TFA, the right to obtain all costs and expenses, including reasonable attorney’s fees and disbursements, incurred by the Covered Employee. PG&E also understands that the MCO provides that if PG&E prevails In any such action, PG&E may be awarded costs and expenses, Including reasonable attorney’s fees and disbursements, from the Covered Employee If the court determines that the Covered Employee’s action was frivolous, vexatious or otherwise an act of bad faith. 9.33.7.12. If PG&E is exempt from the MCO when this TFA Is executed because the cumulative amount of agreements with the City for the fiscal year is less than $25,000 (twenty-five thousand dollars) but PG&E later enters into an agreement or agreements that cause PG&E to exceed that amount in a fiscal year, PG&E shall thereafter be required to comply with the MCO. This obligation arises on the effective date of the agreement that causes the cumulative amount of agreements between the PG&E and the City to exceed $25,000 (twenty-five thousand dollars) in the fiscal year. 9.33.8. Requiring Health Benefits for Covered Employees Unless exempt, PG&E agrees to comply fully with all of the provisions of the Health Care Accountability Ordinance (“HCAO”), as set forth In San Francisco Administrative Code Chapter 12Q, including the remedies provided, and implementing regulations, as the same may be amended from time to time. The provisions of Chapter 12Q are incorporated herein by reference and made a part of this TFA as though filly set forth. Capitalized terms used in this Section and not defined in this TFA shall have the meanings assigned to such terms in Chapter 12Q. To the extent consistent with the requirements of the HCAO, PG&E agrees to the following: 9.33.8.1 For each Covered Employee, PG&E shall provide the appropriate health benefit set forth in Section 12Q.3 of the HCAO. If PG&E chooses to offer the health plan option, such health plan shall meet the minimum standards set forth by the San Francisco Health Commission. 9.33.8.2 Notwithstanding the above, if the PG&E is a small business as defined in Section 12Q.3(d) of the HCAO, it shall have no obligation to comply with part (a) above. 9.33.8.3. PG&E’s failure to comply with the HCAO shall constitute a material breach of this TFA. City shall notify PG&E if such a breach has occurred. If, within thirty (30) days after receiving City’s written notice of a breach of this TFA for violating the HCAO, PG&E fails to cure such breach or, if such breach cannot reasonably be cured within such period of thirty (30) days, PG&E fails to commence efforts to cure within such period, or thereafter fails diligently to pursue such cure to completion, City shall have the right to pursue the remedies set forth in 12Q.5(f)(1-5). Each of these remedies shall be exercisable individually or in combination with any other rights or remedies available to City. 9.33.8.4. Any Subcontract entered into by PG&E shall require the Subcontractor to comply with the requirements of the HCAO and shall contain contractual obligations substantially the same as those set forth in this Section. PG&E shall be responsible for its Subcontractors’ compliance with this Section 9.33.8. If a Subcontractor fails to comply, the City may pursue the remedies set forth in this Section against PG&E based on the Subcontractor’s failure to comply, provided that City has first provided PG&E with notice and an opportunity to cure the violation. 9.33.8.5. PG&E shall not discharge, reduce in compensation, or otherwise discriminate against any employee for notifying City with regard to PG&E’s compliance or anticipated compliance with the requirements of the HCAO, for opposing any practice proscribed by the HCAO, for participating in proceedings related to the HCAO, or for seeking to assert or enforce any rights under the HCAO by any lawful means. 9.33.8.6. PG&E represents and warrants that it is not an entity that was set up, or is being used, for the purpose of evading the intent of the HCAO. 9.33.8.7. PG&E shall keep itself informed of the current requirements of the HCAO. 9.33.8.8. PG&E shall provide reports to the City in accordance with any reporting standards promulgated by the City under the HCAO, including reports on Subcontractors. 9.33.8.9. PG&E shall provide City with access to records pertaining to compliance with HCAO after receiving a written request from City to do so and being provided at least five (5) business days to respond. 9.33.8.10. City may conduct random audits of PG&E upon reasonable notice to ascertain its compliance with HCAO. PG&E agrees to cooperate with City when it conducts such audits. 9.33.8.11. If PG&E is exempt from the HCAO when this TFA is executed because its amount is less than $25,000 (twenty-five thousand dollars), but PG&E later enters into an agreement or agreements that cause PG&E’s aggregate amount of all agreements with City to reach $75,000 (seventy-five thousand dollars), all the agreements shall be thereafter subject to the HCAO. This obligation arises on the effective date of the agreement that causes the cumulative amount of agreements between PG&E and the City to be equal to or greater than $75,000 (seventy-five thousand dollars) in the fiscal year. 9.33.9. Sunshine Ordinance PG&E acknowledges that the City is subject to the San Francisco Sunshine Ordinance, San Francisco Administrative Code, Chapter 67, which inter alia, provides that (1) during the course of negotiations for sole source contracts, all documents, including draft contracts must be available to the public upon written request; (2) contracts and all other records of communications between the City and persons seeking contracts shall be open to inspection immediately upon the award of the contract, and (3) drafts of contracts being negotiated must be made available for public review, upon request, ten (10) days prior approval by a policy body, unless the policy body finds that and articulates how the public interest would be unavoidably and substantially harmed by such disclosure. 9.33.10. Nondisclosure of Private Information The Parties agree to comply fully with and be bound by all of the provisions of Chapter 12M of the San Francisco Administrative Code (the “Nondisclosure of Private Information Ordinance”), including the remedies provided. The provisions of the Nondisclosure of Private Information Ordinance are incorporated herein by reference and made a part of this TFA as though fully set forth. Capitalized terms used in this section and not defined in this TFA shall have the meanings assigned to such terms in the Nondisclosure of Private Information Ordinance. To the extent consistent with the requirements of the Nondisclosure of Private Information Ordinance, the Parties agree to all of the following: 9.33.10.1. Neither Party nor any of its Subcontractors shall disclose Private Information obtained from the other Party in the performance of this TFA to any other Subcontractor, person, or other entity, unless one of the following is true: (i) The disclosure is authorized by this TFA; (ii) The receiving party received advance written approval from the disclosing party to disclose the information; or (iii) The disclosure is required by law or judicial order. 9.33.10. 2. Any disclosure or use of Private Information authorized by this TFA shall be in accordance with any conditions or restrictions stated in this TFA. Any disclosure or use of Private Information authorized by the disclosing party shall be in accordance with any conditions or restrictions stated in the approval. 9.33.10.3. Private Information shall mean any information that: (1) could be used to identify an individual, including without limitation, name, address, social security number, medical information, financial information, date and location of birth, and names of relatives; or (2) the law forbids any person from disclosing about an individual. 9.33.10.4 Any failure of the receiving party to comply with the Nondisclosure of Private Information Ordinance shall be a material breach of this TFA. In such an event, in addition to any other remedies available to it under equity or law, the disclosing Party may terminate this TFA, debar PG&E, or bring a false claim action against the receiving Party. 9.33.11. MacBride Principles Pursuant to San Francisco Administrative Code Section 12.F.5, the City urges companies doing business in Northern Ireland to move towards resolving employment inequities, and encourages such companies to abide by the MacBride Principles. The City urges San Francisco companies to do business with corporations that abide by the MacBride Principles. 9.33.12. Tropical Hardwood and Virgin Redwood Pursuant to §804(b) of the San Francisco Environment Code, the City urges contractors not to import, purchase, obtain, or use for any purpose, any tropical hardwood, tropical hardwood wood product, virgin redwood or virgin redwood wood product.

Transmission Facilities AgreementRavenswood Bore Bay Tunnel Project At the request of the CITY AND COUNTY OF SAN FRANCISCO (“City”), PACIFIC GAS AND ELECTRIC COMPANY (“PG&E”), a California corporation (each being a “Party” or together the “Parties”), hereby agrees to furnish at City's expense certain facilities and perform certain work described in Exhibit A (“Facilities”). PG&E agrees to furnish such Facilities as necessary to provide a temporary connection from PG&E’s Ames – Ravenswood 115 kV line to a new City Substation that will be located in Ravenswood, California (“Project”), as described in Exhibit A. 1. This Transmission Facilities Agreement (“TFA”) includes Exhibit A, Description of Facilities and Estimated Costs. Exhibit A is incorporated by this reference into this TFA. Exhibit A may be revised or superseded by written agreement of the Parties and without formal amendment of the remainder of this TFA. 2. This TFA includes Exhibit B, Provisions Sourced from the Amended and Restated Interconnection Agreement between Pacific Gas and Electric and City and County of San Francisco (“Amended IA”). Exhibit B is incorporated by this reference into this TFA. Exhibit B identifies the following provisions that were sourced from the Amended IA; Sections 1.39., 3.3.2. 3.3.3., 8.3.3., 9.2.5., 9.2.6., 9.5., 9.17., 9.29., and 9.33. The Parties intend and agree that these provisions appearing in Exhibit B are the terms and conditions of this TFA, independent of the existence of the Amended IA. The terms and conditions appearing in Exhibit B shall survive the earlier expiration or termination of the Amended IA. 3. The Parties further agree that once the Project and the Facilities are completed, PG&E will provide electric service to the Project and that the Project will be treated as “municipal load” pursuant to the terms and conditions of the Amended IA. Upon expiration or termination of the Amended IA, such service will be provided under any successor agreement in the same manner as any other “municipal load” site. 4. Definition of "Facilities." Those Facilities described in Exhibit A and requested by City in order to meet the City’s application for the interconnection of City’s Project with PG&E’s electric system, as further explained in Paragraph 7of this TFA. These Facilities are not “Special Facilities” as that term is used in Section 3.3.2 of the Exhibit B. These Facilities are instead “Additional Facilities” as that term is used in Section 3.3.3 of Exhibit B. 5. City has paid PG&E, pursuant to the payment schedule set forth in Exhibit A, for the first two phases of the Project, as specified in Exhibit A. The City understands and agrees that PG&E will not proceed with any remaining Project phase described in Exhibit A until its respective payment is received. To the extent that the City has paid PG&E in full for the work described in Exhibit A for phases 3 and 4 and has otherwise complied with all obligations under this TFA, PG&E agrees to furnish all Facilities and complete all work described in Exhibit A no later than January 31, 2011 (“Facilities Completion Date”). In order for PG&E to complete its work by the Facilities Completion Date, City will have to demonstrate to PG&E’s satisfaction in advance of the Facilities Completion Date that City has completed construction of its substation, and has tested and verified that its substation is complete by December 31, 2010. If the City’s Project is delayed, it will cause a delay in the Facilities Completion Date. The Parties need to coordinate this completion work so as to minimize unnecessary work. 6. Within one hundred and eighty (180) days of completion of all work described in Exhibit A, PG&E shall determine the actual cost of installing the Facilities and shall provide City a final accounting. True-ups shall be conducted pursuant to Section 9.2.5 to the Amended IA. If the actual cost of installation is greater than the total amount that has been paid by City, then PG&E shall bill City for the remaining amount, including interest determined pursuant to Section 35.19a of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission’s (FERC’s or Commission’s) Regulations, 18 C.F.R. § 35.19a. If the actual cost of installation is less than the total amount that has been paid by City, then PG&E shall pay City the difference, including interest determined pursuant to Section 35.19a of FERC’s Regulations, 18 C.F.R. § 35.19a. Pursuant to Section 9.5 of Exhibit B, City may audit PG&E’s supporting documents upon which PG&E bases its actual cost of installing the Facilities. 7. The Facilities identified in Exhibit A to this TFA are owned by, and will remain the property of, PG&E. The Facilities were designed by PG&E at City’s request, for service to City’s Project. This Project and the Facilities are temporary in nature. The City anticipates that the Facilities will remain in place for at least five (5) years. 8. The Project costs identified in Exhibit A do not include Facilities removal costs. PG&E will treat the removal of Facilities as a separate project and will use a separate process to remove Facilities at the appropriate time. With respect to removal: (a) PG&E shall remove all PG&E facilities installed solely for the Project that are deemed by PG&E as no longer used or useful for service. City shall be responsible for the associated costs to remove the PG&E facilities. (b) PG&E shall be entitled to remove and shall have a reasonable time in which to remove any portion of the Facilities located on the City's premises. (c) Pursuant to FERC’s rules and regulations, PG&E will make a filing and obtain FERC acceptance prior to billing City for any Facility Removal Charge, defined as the estimated removal cost, less the estimated salvage value for any Facilities which can be removed, all as determined by PG&E in accordance with its standard accounting practices. (d) City shall pay any Facilities Removal Charge to PG&E within thirty (30) days of FERC’s acceptance of the charge. If the salvage value is greater than the removal cost, PG&E will pay the difference to City within thirty (30) days of removal of Facilities (contingent upon FERC acceptance of the Facility Removal Charge). 9. Because of the magnitude and duration of the Project, at the request of City, PG&E offered a payment schedule that reflects PG&E’s Project expenses and a proposed Project description in four phases. City has already made payments for the first two phases of the Project: Payment for phase 1 was collected pursuant to a Letter of Agreement (“LOA”) designated as Original Sheet Nos. 2046 through 2050 to the Amended IA; and Payment for phase 2 was collected pursuant to a LOA designated as Original Sheet Nos. 2051 and 2052 to the Amended IA. 10. PG&E will provide City and the City will provide PG&E with a monthly status update of construction progress through a status report or a regularly-scheduled progress meeting between PG&E and City staff. Independent of any monthly progress meeting between the parties, to the extent that either party becomes aware of expected or likely delays to its construction schedule, it shall notify the other party immediately of the nature and scope of the potential delays. If the City notifies PG&E of potential delays to its own construction schedule, PG&E shall make best reasonable efforts to maintain its own schedule, including seeking prompt regulatory approval for schedule changes (e.g. from the California Independent System Operator) and assigning available resources to the project to the extent possible and practical. 11. Consistent with Section 9.2.6 of Exhibit B, to the extent that PG&E considers utilizing the fiber between the Ravenswood and Ames Substations that PG&E has installed for the Project for other PG&E projects, PG&E shall provide to City its estimate of the cost savings PG&E would receive by tapping into the Project’s fiber to connect a new PG&E location instead of the cost PG&E would incur if it were to establish or construct an alternative splicing location. The cost and scope of PG&E’s estimated savings from using the City’s funded Facilities (fiber) shall include only the cost to PG&E of installing fiber from the proposed new PG&E site to the splice location on the Ames-Ravenswood fiber. Because the difference between the estimated cost between the two alternatives would reflect PG&E’s cost savings if it were to use the Project’s fiber instead of undertaking a separate effort to tap a comparable, alternative location, that estimated cost savings amount is agreed by the Parties to be reasonable compensation for use of the Project’s fiber (“Compensation Amount”). Thus, the Parties agree that PG&E shall be permitted to use the fiber between Ames and Ravenswood for its own project(s) in exchange for such compensation. Under such circumstances, PG&E shall make a lump sum payment of the Compensation Amount to City upon PG&E’s commencement of construction of the separate PG&E project that will utilize the Ames-Ravenswood fiber. If City and PG&E do not agree on PG&E’s cost savings in advance of PG&E’s use of the Ames-Ravenswood fiber, City at its option may initiate a dispute pursuant to Section 9.29 of Exhibit B. 12. Notwithstanding an agreement or a dispute between the Parties on the Compensation Amount, PG&E will compensate the City for any PG&E use of the Ames-Ravenswood fiber based on the date that PG&E commences work on the separate PG&E project that will utilize the Ames-Ravenswood fiber. The Compensation Amount will be reduced by 0.51% for each month following the Facilities Completion Date that PG&E does not commence construction on the separate PG&E project, until May 2, 2019, after which time PG&E will have no obligation to pay if it commences construction on any new project that uses the Ames-Ravenswood fiber. 13. Where it is necessary to install Facilities on City’s premises, City hereby grants to PG&E: (a) The right to make such installation on City's premises along the shortest practical route thereon with sufficient legal clearance from all structures above and below ground now or hereafter erected or installed on City's premises; and (b) The right of ingress and egress from City's premises at all reasonable hours for any purposes reasonably connected with the installation, operation and maintenance of Facilities. 14. When formal rights of way or easements are required on or over property of City or the property of third parties for the installation of Facilities, City agrees that PG&E shall use all reasonable efforts to obtain such rights of way or easements, which shall be at City’s expense or, if City and PG&E agree, City shall obtain any necessary permanent rights of way or easements, satisfactory to and without cost to PG&E. 15. To the extent that modification is required of other agreements between City and PG&E regarding current or planned transmission projects in the vicinity of or impacted by the Facilities to be installed in connection with this TFA, City and PG&E shall make good faith efforts to agree on such modifications, recognizing that such modifications may be a necessary element of the overall scheme of generation and transmission facilities sought to be installed by PG&E and also recognizing that PG&E has already expended effort and costs to fulfill such other agreements. 16. PG&E shall not be responsible for any delay in completion of the installation of Facilities resulting from shortage of labor or materials, strike, labor disturbance, war, riot, weather conditions, governmental rule, regulation or order, including orders or judgments of any court or regulatory agency, delay in obtaining necessary rights of way and easements, acts of God, delays resulting from PG&E’s responsibility to coordinate certain electric interconnections or modifications with the California Independent System Operator Corporation, or any other cause or condition beyond the control of PG&E. PG&E shall have the right, if for one of the above reasons it is unable to obtain materials or labor for all of its construction requirements, to allocate materials and labor to construction projects which it deems, in its sole discretion, most important to serve the needs of its customers, and any delay in construction, hereunder resulting from such allocation shall be deemed to be a cause beyond PG&E's control. 17. If PG&E is prevented from completing the installation of Facilities for reasons beyond its control as set forth in Paragraph 16 of this TFA after twelve (12) months following the date of this TFA PG&E shall have the right to supersede Exhibit A to this TFA upon at least thirty (30) days' written notice to City. PG&E shall have the right to adjust any amounts paid or required to be paid by City hereunder that may be due based on that portion of the Facilities then completed, if any, utilizing the estimated costs developed by PG&E appearing in Exhibit A to this TFA. Such superseding Exhibit A shall be in substantially the same form as the attached Exhibit A to this TFA and be approved in writing by the Parties hereto. If City does not approve the superseding Exhibit A within thirty (30) days of PG&E’s notice, Exhibit A to this TFA shall terminate, and the provisions of Paragraph 20 of this TFA shall be applied to that portion of Facilities then completed. City also shall reimburse PG&E for any expenses it may have incurred for engineering, surveying, right of way acquisition, restoration and other work associated with that portion of Facilities not installed. The liability provision in Section 9.17 of Exhibit B shall apply to this TFA. 18. New electric extensions and connections, capacity upgrades to existing facilities, conduits and substructures, and the maintenance of facilities, conduits and substructures provided under this TFA shall be installed and made in accordance with fundamental design, installation, ownership, and maintenance provisions of applicable requirements and Good Utility Practice as defined in Section 1.39 of Exhibit B, and interconnection facilities for points of Interconnection at transmission voltage shall be installed and maintained in accordance with PG&E’s Transmission Interconnection Handbook. All charges, payments and refunds shall be made solely under the provisions of this TFA. 19. This TFA shall become effective when it is executed by the Parties hereto. This TFA shall remain in force until one of the following events occurs: (a) Either Party terminates the TFA upon at least thirty (30) days' written notice, except that PG&E may not terminate the TFA except as provided in Paragraph 17 of this TFA or for just cause; or (b) The earlier of the completion of Project construction, true-ups, and removal of Facilities; or May 2, 2019. 20. The Parties recognize and agree that if this TFA is terminated prior to completion of all Project phases appearing in Exhibit A, PG&E may need to engage in additional construction or restoration activities required to restore PG&E’s electric system and the surrounding areas to a safe and operational mode prior to halting work. After receipt of notice from City requesting PG&E to terminate the Project, PG&E will inform City of the post-termination construction and restoration activities that PG&E believes are necessary and appropriate under the circumstances. PG&E may then proceed with necessary post-termination activities with the understanding that post-termination costs shall paid for by City. To the extent that the Parties cannot agree on the reasonable post-termination costs, the Parties will seek to resolve this matter in accordance with the procedures set forth in Section 9.29 of Exhibit B. 21. Nothing contained herein shall be construed as affecting in any way the right of PG&E to unilaterally make application to FERC for a change in rates under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act (“FPA”) and pursuant to FERC’s Rules and Regulations promulgated there under. City shall have the right to protest and object to such changes in rates and otherwise to exercise any and all rights it may have with respect thereto, including its rights under Section 206 of the FPA. The term “rates” as used in the Section shall mean all rates, terms and conditions contained in this TFA. The term “change” shall include, but not be limited to, not only changes in rates and charges by also in the underlying methodology by which such are developed, 22. No transfer or assignment of either Party’s rights, benefits or duties under this TFA shall be effective without the prior written consent of the other Party, which consent shall not be withheld unreasonably; provided, however, that this Paragraph 22 shall not apply to interests that arise by reason of any deed of trust, mortgage, indenture or security agreement granted or executed by either Party. No partial assignment of Party’s rights, benefits or duties shall be permitted under this TFA unless otherwise agreed to in writing by the Parties. Any successor to or transferee or assignee of the rights or obligations of a Party, whether by voluntary transfer, judicial sale, foreclosure sale or otherwise, shall be subject to all terms and conditions of this TFA to the same extent as though such successor, transferee, or assignee were an original party. Any dispute arising from this TFA shall be resolved in accordance with the procedures of Section 9.29 of the Exhibit B. 23. The total PG&E estimated construction costs for the Project shall include the Income Tax Component of Contribution related to the Project in accordance with Section J of PG&E’s Electric Preliminary Statements. 24. This TFA may be executed in any number of counterparts, each of which shall be an original and all of which together shall constitute one instrument. 25. This TFA may be amended or modified only by the written agreement of the Parties, except as otherwise specifically provided herein. 26. This TFA, inclusive of Exhibits A and B, constitutes the complete and final expression of the rights and obligations of the Parties in connection with the subject matter of this TFA and is intended as a complete and exclusive statement of the terms of their agreement which supersedes all prior and contemporaneous offers, promises, representations, negotiations, discussions, communications, and contracts which may have been made in connection with the subject matter of this TFA. Dated this 6th day of November, 2009.
